                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d175">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5131/1076: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-29T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 29, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>159. Your 368, April 27, 2 p.m. Public notice of intention to negotiate a trade
                    agreement with France will be issued tomorrow <pb facs="0296" n="220"
                        xml:id="pg_220"/> afternoon.<note n="12" xml:id="d175fn12">See Department of
                        State, <hi rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, May 4, 1935, p. 301.</note>
                    June 24 will be fixed as the date for the public hearings before the Committee
                    for Reciprocity Information.</p>
                <p>Under present instructions from the President to the Secretary of the Treasury,
                    France is to enjoy the benefits of the Belgian trade agreement so long as the
                    present directions from the President are not modified. New instructions will
                    now be issued to the Secretary of the Treasury, placing France in the same
                    category with certain other countries with which we are negotiating trade
                    agreements, and the benefits of the Belgian and other agreements will be
                    extended to France for a period of <hi rend="italic">6</hi> months as from April
                    1. We of course hope that a satisfactory agreement will have been reached before
                    the expiration of that period.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
